			<div class="POA_hero_box">
				<h2 class="hero_text" id="POA_hero_text">Elder Abuse Attorneys</h2>
			</div>

			<div class="main_content_video">
				<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/P5iSllH4AA0" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
			</div>

			<div class="wills_header_text_box">
				<h1 class="main_header">The Two Main Types of Elder Abuse Cases</h1>
				<h5 class="heading_description">There are generally two types of elder abuse cases that we see, medical malpractice and general negligence cases. 

				Traditionally, these cases have fallen under the category of medical malpractice because an elderly person is receiving some type of medical care, whether that be in some type of nursing home or through home healthcare. If a physician, or what the law calls a Qualified Healthcare Provider, falls below the standard of care, then they may have committed medical malpractice. Then if the healthcare provider is a part of the patient’s compensation fund, then the case must go before a panel of doctors and these physicians determine whether or not malpractice was committed. Then the case may proceed through the courts. 

				Generally anything that does not fall under the medical malpractice category is going to be considered a general negligence case. The main thing to remember about a negligence case is that the word negligence derives from the word neglect. These cases involve any type of situation where one party has neglected another party and they should not have. What we see is that this can involve anyone who is involved in providing services to the elderly. That is a broad range of companies and can include companies involved in transport, preparing meals, home health care attendants and even just sitters. Those organizations all owe a basic duty to the person they are providing services for, and when that organization breaches that duty then there is a case. The breach can be very simple. Perhaps someone is meant to be a sitter for 24 hours and was only there for half of the day, or they were there but fell asleep. Finally, there must be some type of damages involved in order for there to be a successful case.</h5>
			</div>

			<div class="main_content_video">
				<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YKucEjXJHwg" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
			</div>
				
			<div class="wills_header_text_box">
				<h1 class="main_header">Who Can Commit Elder Abuse?</h1>
				<h5 class="heading_description">We are often asked who is an elder abuse case against? Does it have to be a nursing home? The answer is no, it can be against any person or organization that provides service to the elderly. It can be as broad as that and there are many companies that fall under that category. Helpful examples can be hospitals, nursing homes, sitters, transportation companies and meal preparers, but basically it can be any company that aids the elderly.</h5>
			</div>

			<div class="main_content_video">
				<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/8tU4j3vwRWU" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
			</div>

			<div class="wills_header_text_box">
				<h1 class="main_header">Elder Abuse & Estate Law Issues</h1>
				<h5 class="heading_description">Oftentimes when we are talking about elder abuse cases, the elder person can be incapacitated. They can either not have their mental faculties or not be able to speak for themselves. In that situation, a critical question for us as the attorneys is who can institute the lawsuit on behalf of the victim. If someone has a power of attorney, then potentially that person could pursue the lawsuit on the victim’s behalf. We would have to review the power of attorney to confirm what authority it gives. Alternatively, an interdiction always grants that authority. The interdiction, sometimes called a guardianship in other states, gives an individual the legal authority to act on another’s behalf. Being able to go forward with the case procedurally is a critical element when it comes to elder abuse cases. This is particularly true because deadlines do apply and there are statutes of limitation. For that reason, it is important to talk to an elder abuse attorney who understands these processes.</h5>
			</div>

			<div class="main_content_video">
				<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Ku6CJSvE8qU" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
			</div>

			<div class="wills_header_text_box">
				<h1 class="main_header">Why Do We Defend the Elderly?</h1>
				<h5 class="heading_description">We do what some have called “Elder Law,” but what does that really entail? Most people know that includes traditional aspects such as drafting wills, creating trusts, and any kind of estate planning in general. But unfortunately one thing we have learned is that the elderly amongst us are certainly some of the most vulnerable, and so part of our practice dedicated to helping them does include seeking justice on their behalf if they have been wronged or injured in some way. Our diverse litigation background and our detailed knowledge and experience with elder law issues puts us in a position to be able to prosecute these cases strongly. </h5>
			</div>

