					<h5 class="mini_content">There are many different types of powers of attorney and various names and titles used to describe each particular type of power of attorney, however it is important to note Louisiana law only recognizes two (2) actual categories of powers of attorney:</h5>
					<ol class="witness_qualifications">
						<li><h5><b>General Power of Attorney</b> - A general power of attorney grants all the ordinary powers of administration, this would include all authority to handle and execute the principal’s affairs, including but not limited to opening and withdrawing accounts, signing documents, alienating, acquiring, encumbering, or leasing property (which requires express consent), and all other other general affairs.</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5><b>Special Power of Attorney</b> - A special power of attorney grants special powers, such as making inter vivos donations, accepting or renouncing a succession, contracting a loan, entering into a compromise, contracting or granting authority to execute a particular financial transaction or sale, or making healthcare decisions, such as surgery, medical expenses, nursing home residency, and medication.</h5></li>
					</ol>
					<h5 class="mini_content">Within these two categories of powers of attorney there are designated types of powers of attorney which operate differently.  A nonexclusive list (terms more commonly referred in common law jurisdictions outside of Louisiana) are: (1) Non-durable powers of attorney,  (2) durable powers of attorney, (3) special or limited powers of attorney, (4) medical powers of attorney, and (5) springing powers of attorney.</h5>
					<ol class="witness_qualifications">
						<li><h5>A <b>non-durable</b> power of attorney is one that is set for a specific time period, meaning the agent’s authority over the principal lasts for a set period of time.  For example an individual could grant a sibling (an agent) a special power of attorney to sell his or her home while out of the country.  The period of time would only last while the individual is out of the country and would be limited to a specific date and to a specific transaction, such as closing.</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>A <b>durable</b> power of attorney is one that upon taking effect lasts indefinitely or expires upon principal’s death.  For lack of better words it is durable (long lasting).  Often, an individual will execute a general power of attorney to a loved one which kicks in or takes effect upon the individual losing mental capacity (capacity of which is generally certified by two (2) physicians or the individual’s regular treating physician).  Upon certification by physician(s), the general power  last upon the principal reobtaining capacity or upon death.</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>A <b>springing</b> power of attorney is one that takes effect when a specific event or occurrence takes place.  For lack of better words, the power of attorney springs into place upon the an event.  For example an individual could create a special power of attorney that is a springing power of attorney that takes effect upon the individual leaves the country on a particular enumerated date.</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>A <b>medical</b> power of attorney is a special power of attorney (as defined above) which grants an agent authority to make all healthcare and medical decisions for the principal. It can be durable or spring into effect depending on how it is drafted and designated.</h5></li>
					</ol>
