			<h1 class="content_heading">When Is The Power Of Attorney Over?</h1>
			<div class="witnesses_section">
				<div class="qualifications">
					<h5 class="mini_content">There are several different scenarios that can lead to the end of the power of attorney. Some of them happen depending on what the parties involved decide, and some of them happen automatically.

					A power of attorney <b>terminates by choice</b> when either of the following two events happen:
					</h5>
					<ul class="witness_qualifications">
						<li><h5>Whenever the principal says so; OR</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>When the person given the power of attorney tells the principal that he is resigning or renouncing his authority.</h5></li>
					</ul>

					<h5 class="mini_content">A power of attorney <b>terminates automatically</b> when any of the following events happen:</h5>
					<ul class="witness_qualifications">
						<li><h5>Either the principal or the person given the power of attorney dies; OR</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>The person given the power of attorney is interdicted (declared by a court to be mentally incapable of making their own decisions); OR</h5></li>
						<li class="internal_list_item"><h5>The principal has been interdicted and a guardian or “curator” has been qualified for him or her.</h5></li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>

